WEBVTT

00:01.240 --> 00:12.580
How did you get interested in costuming? Well actually I've always been
interested in pretty clothes as it were but I actually to go to where I got

00:12.580 --> 00:19.960
interest in costuming you kind of have to go back to the beginning of fandom.
And for me I'm been interested in science fiction literature since around the

00:19.960 --> 00:28.080
beginning of junior high when I discovered that I didn't have all that many
friends and there wasn't much else to do and I was a ravenous reader and I read

00:28.080 --> 00:36.980
all the horror stories in the book in the library and all the dog stories in the
library, and I didn't like mysteries, and I didn't like romances, and all that

00:36.980 --> 00:44.500
was left was science fiction, so I grudgingly took science fiction down off the
shelf and started, and I've been hooked ever since. It was kind of like the most

00:44.500 --> 00:53.580
wonderful thing I'd ever discovered, a genre of literature where your
imagination can run completely wild, and for a long time, I knew absolutely

00:53.580 --> 01:02.320
nothing about fandom, and then I discovered Star Trek. interesting enough my
stepfather was watching it and I happen to sit down one evening and I was hooked

01:02.320 --> 01:10.360
from then on because it was a wonderful world of the future where all kinds of
imaginative things were happening but more importantly it was still a world

01:10.360 --> 01:19.000
about people and it was people conquering the future and conquering problems and
most of all conquering themselves and at the time that was my biggest problem

01:19.000 --> 01:27.620
was trying to learn how to deal with myself and deal with the people around me
so I became an avid Trekkie and I still didn't know about fandom. But one day

01:27.620 --> 01:35.480
after Star Trek, there was a big advertisement for a Star Trek convention in
Dallas, and it was going to have some of the stars there and everything, and I'd

01:35.480 --> 01:46.560
never heard of such a thing. But it sounded like a lot of fun, so we went down,
and then I ran into nearly 1,500 to 2,000 fans who also liked Star Trek, who

01:46.560 --> 01:55.900
also had a reason for coming to science fiction and fantasy, and had been
touched by Star Trek because of this feeling they had. And, all of a sudden, I

01:55.900 --> 02:04.960
had a family and a place to belong, and I've been an avid fan ever since, going
to as many conventions as I could. And one aspect of this convention was

02:04.960 --> 02:12.460
costuming, and I'd always been sort of interested in theatre and that sort of
thing, but never really involved. But here were all these people who weren't

02:12.460 --> 02:19.580
really into theatre and weren't performers, but they had all these wonderful
costumes and were going up and doing the masquerades. The next time they had a

02:19.580 --> 02:30.380
convention, I was ready and I had my first costume. It was a very poorly made
mirror mirror costume from the Star Trek episode Mirror Mirror. But it was a

02:30.380 --> 02:39.000
beginning and it was something and all of a sudden I was involved and I had a
part in a world where in my life I didn't have much of anything that I really

02:39.000 --> 02:50.980
belonged to. And through fandom and science fiction and belonging to that world
I eventually learned how to belong in a normal world again and basically it

02:50.980 --> 02:59.240
changed my entire life. I actually even became popular in high school, which at
the time that I started in fandom, I would have thought that popularity was

02:59.240 --> 03:10.940
something I would never see. So, and then it grew from there. I became a theater
and drama major at UTA and I now work as a professional singer and performer and

03:10.940 --> 03:20.400
do a lot of costuming with that job and freelance costuming, but my first love
is still making characters come alive on the stage at science fiction and

03:20.400 --> 03:28.200
fantasy conventions because I think that what I was searching for at the time
was a reality I could fit into and I think that's what the other fans are

03:28.200 --> 03:39.900
searching for and The Masquerade gives me a chance to make that dream become a
reality. Give us a specific example of bringing a character to life. All right,

03:40.080 --> 03:51.960
for example, one of our most successful costume skits that we designed, and I
had some other people with me at the time. We went to WorldCon in Boston, and we

03:51.960 --> 04:01.300
had a young fellow who was a good friend of mine, and my little sister did a
Star Wars skit together. But what they did was the lights darkened, and the Star

04:01.300 --> 04:11.120
Wars theme came up, and all of a sudden, Luke Skywalker came flying through the
air, were doing somersaults onto the stage, stopped, and did a one-handed

04:11.120 --> 04:21.600
handstand very precariously balancing using the Force to hold him up, and then
Yoda came slowly onto the stage, nodding wisely, and instructing him on the use

04:21.600 --> 04:29.080
of the Force. He didn't get it right the first time, then he tried again the
second time, and finally succeeded with a perfect one-handed handstand,

04:29.080 --> 04:36.820
balancing with the use of the Force, and then leapt up, did a couple more flying
leaps and somersaults in the middle of the air across the stage, and left

04:36.820 --> 04:48.680
standing ovation by 9,000 screaming people who, for them, Star Wars was alive.
And that particular skit that was one that I designed and my little sister and

04:48.680 --> 05:00.780
boyfriend at the time took part in, one the first prize for best presentation at
a World Con. And there were about 150 entrants in that masquerade. But this was

05:00.780 --> 05:09.460
special because all of the sudden their characters were alive. Another one that
I have done has been extremely Wait a second. Back up and give us a genesis of

05:09.460 --> 05:23.040
how you put this all together, how the costumes got it, how the idea for the
action, the plot storyline that you had. Give us a little rendition of how that

05:23.040 --> 05:31.380
came together. Okay. The way that skit came together is that we were sitting
around, and we wanted to go to WorldCon. Of course, everyone wanted to take part

05:31.380 --> 05:38.280
in the Masquerade, because it's kind of your chance to be a star, as it were.
And the audiences at Worldcon are so large that it's probably the largest

05:38.280 --> 05:47.040
audience you will ever have even if you do Broadway. My little sister was very
interested in performing but she only likes to perform behind a mask because

05:47.040 --> 05:59.640
that way she's more secure. And my boyfriend was a gymnast and so we decided we
needed to do something to do a useful thing with these gymnastic skills. Just

05:59.640 --> 06:09.980
recently we'd been asked by a theater to come and do a Star Wars performance for
their opening of Empire. And so we went and did the opening and built him a Luke

06:09.980 --> 06:18.040
Skywalker outfit for the opening. And when he was there, he was playing around
and discovered that he could do most of the force stunts just by virtue of his

06:18.040 --> 06:27.660
gymnastic training because he'd been like fifth in the state in gymnastics. And
then my little sister started playing around and rehearsing and working on

06:27.660 --> 06:37.700
looking like Yodon, walking like Yodon, having the mannerisms. And it dawned on
me, since we had a special talent here, we could use that to bring this special

06:37.700 --> 06:46.580
thing to fans, who probably never dreamed of the fact that the force could be
made to come alive. If we hadn't had a gymnast, we could've figured out a way to

06:46.580 --> 06:56.100
do it with wires, but it was that much more special, because it was real and
live. That was how that particular act came together. I also have another one

06:56.100 --> 07:06.280
that has been extremely successful. is called Morgan Le Fay. And the character,
basically, I was sitting around trying to think of what is a really way out

07:06.280 --> 07:14.780
character that's not all that well-known, but that could command the stage and
make that same kind of reality come about. And it occurred to me that very

07:14.780 --> 07:23.160
little has been done with the sorceress Morgan Le Fay, who's from the Arthurian
legend and who was the one that eventually defeated Merlin. And I thought if I

07:23.160 --> 07:33.080
can make this character do a spell on stage so that the audience really believes
it, that that would be an excellent kind of costume to do. So I designed the

07:33.080 --> 07:40.540
costume. And of course, it's different than designing a costume for a movie
character or a television character because it was completely up to my

07:40.540 --> 07:54.040
imagination what I wanted to do with it. So I used a lot of reds and blacks and
lots of gold to create a total effect of color but somber, evil color and made a

07:54.040 --> 08:06.040
very large headdress with lots of sparkles on it to catch the light and designed
it in such a way so that it would give the impression of an evil sorceress who

08:06.040 --> 08:14.240
had a lot of power and was a ruler in her own right and designed the cloak so
that it would actually fold out into a half circle so that it would look like

08:14.240 --> 08:23.920
bat wings on the back. The costume was beautiful, but that's not enough. the
next thing I did was I wanted to design something for her to do. So I wrote a

08:23.920 --> 08:31.700
spell. I decided that she would probably be pissed at someone because she's
usually angry at someone most of the time and was famous for destroying people

08:31.700 --> 08:40.280
and things. So I wrote a spell wherein she was summoning the spirits of darkness
who came and gathered around her and then she sends them off to go destroy all

08:40.280 --> 08:49.900
her enemies, which is nice, but again, that wasn't enough. So the next thing I
did is I started listening to albums, trying to find some music that would

08:49.900 --> 08:59.440
summon the mood because I wanted a very somber, evil mood, sort of like the
building of a thunderstorm. And I finally came across in the album Lion and

08:59.440 --> 09:10.260
Winter a very somber, evil-sounding piece of music which sounded very much like
a thunderstorm building, coming into the foreground and then receding. And then

09:10.260 --> 09:19.560
I worked the spell so that it would work exactly around the crescendos. And then
I added a soundtrack record which had thunder and lightning on it, and went into

09:19.560 --> 09:27.700
my handy dandy little stereo set in the middle of living room, bought a bunch of
patch cords from Radio Shack so the room looked like Spaghetti'sville, and

09:27.700 --> 09:36.900
patched it all together. Using a normal hand-mic and a reverb effect from the
speakers being on at the same time as a recording, managed to get an evil

09:36.900 --> 09:46.540
reverberating sound to the voice, lightning and thunder in the background, this
awesome evil music building and flowing in a high climax and fading out in the

09:46.540 --> 09:55.240
distance so I had a wonderful soundtrack and if the mic failed I'd still be fine
because I had it all on tape. The next thing I did was I needed something else,

09:55.640 --> 10:03.700
something special that would still make it believable. Now the sound was there
and the sight was there but it needed something extra. So I went down to the

10:03.700 --> 10:15.380
magic store and bought a special magic gizmo and some flash paper and the way
the actual skit came off was something like this. The stage would darken and

10:15.380 --> 10:25.740
then you'd see a red glow moving up onto the stage and you'd see just the
outline of this bizarre golden mask and headdress and a red-garbed woman holding

10:25.740 --> 10:35.240
the red globe. Then the music starts and starts to build and all of a sudden the
spell starts and then suddenly there's a burst of flame from the red globe. And

10:35.240 --> 10:42.520
as the spill builds and she starts summoning the darkness the room gets darker
for a moment and then there's another burst of flame and the room starts to

10:42.520 --> 10:52.280
lighten just a little bit and the spell builds and builds until finally she
banishes the light from her and says darkness be gone and then blast this huge

10:52.280 --> 11:01.720
shot of fire blue flame straight up into the sky and the darkness is gone and
then she tells you that she is Morgan Le Fay and then demonstrates the costume

11:01.720 --> 11:13.300
and shows the wide wings of the bat and slowly walks off as the thunder fades
into the distance again I got a standing ovation the The costume has never not

11:13.300 --> 11:23.240
won a prize. It has always been first and second everywhere I've taken it. And
there are better costumes, but it comes to life, and that's what the people are

11:23.240 --> 11:31.720
looking for, is a way to bring their fantasies and their dreams into reality so
they can touch them, so it's something they can really have a tangible

11:31.720 --> 11:42.960
experience from. I've seen you do your thing before, and it's not just walking
up, showing the costume, striking a pose and leaving you have a performance that

11:42.960 --> 11:50.700
you do exactly just

11:50.700 --> 11:58.800
reiterate a little bit of why you decided to add that extra dimension well I've
seen a lot of masquerade and when I started the thing was that everyone walked

11:58.800 --> 12:11.080
up there turned around and walked off and it was nice but after about the 50th
person, it can get real boring. And since the Masquerade was designed with an

12:11.080 --> 12:18.780
audience in mind, it seemed to me that there should be something more
entertaining for them. And some people were doing little bitty skits and

12:18.780 --> 12:28.000
flourishes if they had a sword and stuff like that. But it still wasn't enough.
It was still Johnny in a costume trying to show off his sword, or every now and

12:28.000 --> 12:35.780
then there'd be a nice skit that was really funny, and that was the high point.
But very few high points for a lot of people going through the line and showing

12:35.780 --> 12:45.040
their costumes, and I started thinking about, well, what is a masquerade really
supposed to be? What is it all about? And also, there was the fact that although

12:45.040 --> 12:54.740
I'm not a bad seamstress, neither am I equipped to go work for Warner Brothers
Studios or something like that. And it occurred to me that if I was going to

12:54.740 --> 13:02.400
win, and if I was going to capture these people's imagination, I'd do something
more than walk up there with a brilliant costume turn around and walk off and

13:02.400 --> 13:10.280
also I think part of it's the actress in me, if I'm going to do something and
play like I'm a character I want to play like I'm really that character I want

13:10.280 --> 13:17.880
to feel it and be it and make it as real as possible because it's more fun for
me you know if I'm going to be Princess Lea I'd like to have a chance to really

13:17.880 --> 13:27.360
feel like I'm Princess Lea out to save the Rebel Alliance or whatever and it
seemed like that was what was lacking, the people were trying for that They

13:27.360 --> 13:35.020
wanted to do that, they wouldn't have built the costume if they didn't want for
a minute to feel like they were that hero or villain or whatever, but the extra

13:35.020 --> 13:44.320
touches weren't there. And so I decided that that would be a good thing to do.
And when I got to Worldcon, I discovered that that was what was preferred. And

13:44.320 --> 13:53.340
as a matter of fact, now most Worldcon costumes are designed with the idea of
trying to bring that character to life in some way, and make a show of it even

13:53.340 --> 14:00.580
if it's only a a minute long because most of them it's good not to do it over a
minute or a minute and a half. But even in a minute or a minute and a half, you

14:00.580 --> 14:10.520
can bring it to life and when I choose a character to do and I'm trying to
decide what I'm going to do for the next costume, the first question I ask is

14:10.520 --> 14:18.320
what is it about this character that is special that will bring this character
to life? What can I do to make this character stand out so it's not just a

14:18.320 --> 14:25.400
costume on a stage? And if the answer is nothing, if there's nothing special
about that character, that costume, I won't do it.

14:29.720 --> 14:30.360
Okay.

14:33.100 --> 14:44.860
There is costuming for movie characters and for literary characters. Which one
is more challenging? I would assume it would be the literary characters. But

14:44.860 --> 14:53.060
what are the different challenges doing a movie character versus a written
character? Well, of course, there are the two kinds, like you mentioned, the

14:53.060 --> 15:05.920
media and the literary. Actually, it depends. I think one of my greatest
challenges was recreating the characters from Heavy Metal, which I did last

15:05.920 --> 15:17.500
year, because the costumes were designed on animated figures, and I was trying
to recreate them onto live-action figures exact in detail. And for me, it is

15:17.500 --> 15:27.440
almost harder to do an exact detailed replica of an existing costume than to
just be able to let my imagination go wild and do whatever. And the reason for

15:27.440 --> 15:34.260
that is if you get it wrong, they're going to know, where if you're doing a
costume from your imagination, you can make it very elaborate, but if something

15:34.260 --> 15:42.600
doesn't work, you can say, oh well, I didn't like that effect anyway. Let's do
something different. It takes more time and you have to put a lot more detail

15:42.600 --> 15:53.580
onto an imaginary costume, but it takes an extreme amount of discipline and
creativity to do an exact reproduction. Unfortunately, the exact reproductions

15:53.580 --> 16:04.440
usually do the least winning unless you've got something special to add to them
because the inspiration for the costumes is available to anyone. You know, go to

16:04.440 --> 16:15.940
the movies, go to TV, you can see the costumes. And so we tend to have an
overrun of Starfleet uniforms and Jawas and Stormtroopers and I remember one

16:15.940 --> 16:26.040
masquerade. We had seven Han Solos and five Luke Skywalkers and six Princess
Leias. Wookiees are a little harder, but there have been two of them on

16:26.040 --> 16:34.720
occasion. But yet they're very challenging to do to get them right, and a lot of
times you can spot that one's not quite right. But they don't do the most

16:34.720 --> 16:43.840
winning. So usually when I do a media costume, it's not necessarily aimed for
the masquerade. It's usually aimed for something to bring the convention itself

16:43.840 --> 16:54.360
to life by wearing around the halls. The exception being Tarna. We had a show we
could put on with Tarna. We recreated part of the movie on stage and were able

16:54.360 --> 17:01.680
to do it convincingly in such a way, again, as to bring the character to life.
But if I couldn't have done that, I would have never put the character on the

17:01.680 --> 17:09.980
stage just to show off the costume, even though it was actually harder to build
than Morgana, which was an imaginary costume. I'm glad you brought that up about

17:09.980 --> 17:22.160
parading through the halls before the main show. I want to get on that. When you
do a literary costume, are there any authors, because of the way they write or

17:22.160 --> 17:34.620
the way they describe things, who you tend to gravitate toward when you do
characters? Actually, what I prefer to do when I'm doing a literary character is

17:34.620 --> 17:45.520
I prefer to pick a character that has the least description about what they are
and the most potential. Gods and goddesses are wonderful. Spirits are wonderful.

17:46.320 --> 17:55.280
Things that you really can't imagine as belonging in the real world are the best
things when you're doing an imaginary costume. For example, if you're doing a

17:55.280 --> 18:05.540
snow spirit, you can go absolutely crazy on cloaks and full-spread backdrops and
headdresses that reach from here to heaven and back and that kind of thing that

18:05.540 --> 18:12.640
are absolutely ridiculous for a real person to be wearing around the streets.
But if you're talking about a mythical being or a creature or a spirit, you can

18:12.640 --> 18:21.340
go absolutely hog wild and they look the best on stage. A set that we're working
on right now, as a matter of fact, we're doing a series called The Three Fates

18:21.340 --> 18:31.580
and we're doing birth, death, and destiny. Again, these are spirits. They're
characters that don't have any actual human parameters, so we can go absolutely

18:31.580 --> 18:40.160
nuts on the costume as far as just getting the feeling across and doing anything
we want to make something super flamboyant. It's much harder to do an actual

18:40.160 --> 18:48.620
real living character because, again, you have to deal with something that's
possible that a person would actually wear around and still make it beautiful

18:48.620 --> 18:56.220
enough and interesting enough that it takes over the stage. and if you don't
have the skit or the characterization to go with it, no matter what you do or

18:56.220 --> 18:58.320
how well you do it, it's not going to cut it.

19:02.360 --> 19:12.920
Okay, what about the wearing of the costumes during the con? You may not wear
the same costume on stage that you do down the hall. Yeah, I've noticed at the

19:12.920 --> 19:24.720
cons there are the masquerade costumes, And then there are the everyday wear,
not state-of-the-roll. The everyday costume, the ones you wear during the-

19:24.720 --> 19:34.700
Exactly, exactly. Hall costumes versus stage costumes. What's the difference?
The difference is that a hall costume, for example, Starfleet uniforms are

19:34.700 --> 19:41.200
wonderful hall costumes. They're terrible on the stage unless you've written a
play or a skit to go with them, and which is the play or skit that does the

19:41.200 --> 19:50.260
winning, not the costume. but they're wonderful for costumes because you can
really be from the Enterprise down on shore leave looking through a bazaar or

19:50.260 --> 19:58.080
going to lectures or whatever and there's a lot of the let's pretend We're
bringing it to life in the everyday kind of syndrome with real people and this

19:58.080 --> 20:07.180
is when you can sink your teeth into a live character because this is where the
live character type of outfits work so well, you can be Conan or his lady or you

20:07.180 --> 20:18.940
can be a stormtrooper or Luke and Han and Leia, you know, on and get into the
everyday, let's pretend aspect of it where these characters would die on stage,

20:18.940 --> 20:26.020
unless you have something special, you don't have to be able to do anything to
wear a Hulk costume. And yet at the same time, you can have a lot of fun. It's

20:26.020 --> 20:34.240
fun for other people because it brings the convention to life. Hey, they came
here to, to get into science fiction and fantasy and wow, look, there's Han Solo

20:34.240 --> 20:43.280
right over there, all of a sudden it's special for them. Masqueragers and hall
costumers are doing a service actually, they're making fun for themselves

20:43.280 --> 20:51.480
because they can pretend but they're making fun for everyone else because
they're making it come alive. And that's why conventions are as popular as they

20:51.480 --> 20:59.580
are now anyway is because the fans are looking for a way to bring the whole
thing out, to make it more real, to touch the authors that make this magic, to

20:59.580 --> 21:08.640
touch the artists that create the magic, to make it all something more tangible
than just what they see in a book. And the hall costumes are absolutely

21:08.640 --> 21:16.280
essential for that. And then again, we have a different kind of hall costume,
which is the medieval society costume. And none of these are stage costumes.

21:16.420 --> 21:24.720
They never are. Most of them are much better made than stage costumes because
they're clothes. And the medieval society usually shows up at conventions to

21:24.720 --> 21:35.220
promote their club and to bring a touch of the fantasy element into it and bring
the medieval ages to life and so forth. And they have a completely different

21:35.220 --> 21:47.240
kind of costume, but again, it's a hall costume. About the medieval society, are
you speaking to the Society for Creative Anachronism? There are several. There

21:47.240 --> 21:56.340
is the Society for Creative Anachronisms, which is most prevalent here in the
Southwest, and it's nationwide, but down here it's the only one we have. There

21:56.340 --> 22:06.160
also are the Marklanders, which are a slightly different variation on the same
kind of theme. I believe there are one or two others, but those are the two

22:06.160 --> 22:15.480
major ones. So there's more than one kind of medieval society, but the major
one, largest one, is the Society for Creative Anachronisms. And they recreate

22:15.480 --> 22:23.640
all aspects of medieval life. But since fantasy is such a big part of the
science fiction and fantasy genre, and since most fantasies are based on a

22:23.640 --> 22:33.260
medieval way of life, they fit right in to the convention scene. Which kind of
costumes are more interesting to work on? Science fiction type of costume or a

22:33.260 --> 22:45.940
fantasy costume? Actually, it really depends. They're all fun to work on if
you've got a good idea and some place to go with it. And it doesn't matter

22:45.940 --> 22:55.100
whether they're science fiction or fantasy. Most of the better costumes are
fantasy, simply because fantasy is so open-ended that you can go really berserk

22:55.100 --> 23:03.600
on what you're doing with it. But I have seen some really phenomenal ideas to do
for science fiction costumes as well. The problem with science fiction is that

23:03.600 --> 23:12.600
most of it is technical and nuts and bolts and space suits and things like that,
and you have to really reach to find a creative way to do something different.

23:12.600 --> 23:23.700
But I have seen some really phenomenal things done with robotics and weaponry
and nuts and bolts things. I prefer the fantasy-type things because you don't

23:23.700 --> 23:33.200
have any limitations. You don't have to make it look like it could work. You can
just go bananas on it. But then again, McCaffrey has turned dragons into a

23:33.200 --> 23:43.080
science fiction character, which were once totally fantasy, so who can say?
They're both equally challenging if you just have the right idea and an

23:43.080 --> 23:54.000
interesting enough idea to make it challenging. at a masquerade um is there an
error of competition or do people help each other and admire each other it's

